## 1. Introduction

The Gravwell GitHub Kit provides a set of tools and pre-built resources to analyze GitHub activity efficiently. Use it for monitoring pull requests, investigating users and actors, and correlating GitHub data with IPs or domains.

***

## 2. Tags & Macros

The Gravwell GitHub Kit makes use of the following tags:
- github: used to tag general GitHub data & events
- github-audit: used to tag GitHub audit events

The Gravwell GitHub Kit makes use of the following macros:
- $GITHUB: Necessary for any queries within the Gravwell GitHub Kit to run properly; github
    - Usage: tag=$GITHUB
    - **Important:** If your "Tag-Name" is different than what is in the Macro, **NONE** of the Queries, Scheduled Searches, Alerts, Flows, or Dashboards will work!
        - This is configured during kit installation, and can be changed later on in the Macros section within Gravwell.
- $GITHUB\_AUDIT: Necessary for any queries within the Gravwell GitHub Kit to run properly; github-audit
    - Usage: tag=$GITHUB_AUDIT
    - **Important:** If your "Tag-Name" is different than what is in the Macro, **NONE** of the Queries, Scheduled Searches, Alerts, Flows, or Dashboards will work!
        - This is configured during kit installation, and can be changed later on in the Macros section within Gravwell.
- $GITHUB\_ALERT\_META: This macro standardizes output for GitHub queries that are being alerted upon.
    - Usage $GITHUB\_ALERT\_META(priority[string], message[string])
        - i.e. $GITHUB\_ALERT\_META("Medium", "GitHub Account Changed")
- $GITHUB\_ALERT\_RECIPIENT: This is the address to which GitHub Alert Flows will be sent to.
    - Replace "replace\_me@with\_valid\_recipient.address"
- $GITHUB\_ALERT\_SENDER: This is the address to which GitHub Alert Flows will be sent from.
    - Replace "replace\_me@with\_valid\_sender.address"

***

## 3. Query Library

We've created several baseline queries to interact with your GitHub data. These queries serve as a foundation for custom analysis and can be adapted to your specific needs.

***

## 4. Dashboards

The kit includes a variety of dashboards designed to provide insights into GitHub activity:

#### 4.1 GitHub Overview
- A general overview of your GitHub data, summarizing key metrics.
#### 4.2 GitHub Pull Requests
- Provides an overview of all Pull Requests across repositories, including their status and activity trends.
#### 4.3 GitHub User/Actor Investigation
- Intended for investigating specific GitHub users/actors, including their activity and interactions.
    - Actor is the user who performed the action.
    - User is the user who had the action performed against their account.
#### 4.4 GitHub IP Investigation
- Used for investigating specific IP addresses, including their activity and interactions.

***

## 5. Resources

These lookup files enhance queries and dashboards by providing contextual information about GitHub activity.

#### 5.1 github\_audit\_events
- A lookup file for GitHub Audit Event information.
    - **Fieldnames:** category, name, description
#### 5.2 github\_cidr
- A CIDR lookup file for mapping IP addresses in queries.
    - **Fieldnames:** company, category, CIDR
#### 5.3 github\_domains
- A lookup file for GitHub domains and their associated categories.
    - **Fieldnames:** company, category, domain
#### 5.4 Example Queries Using Resources
### Example 1: Pull Requests with IP Lookup
```query
  tag=$GITHUB_AUDIT json action~"pull_request.create" repo SRC
  | alias SRC src_ip
  | iplookup -r github_cidr -e src_ip CIDR category
  | table
```

### Example 2: Pull Requests with Audit Event and IP Lookup
```query
  tag=$GITHUB_AUDIT json action~"pull_request.create" repo SRC
  | alias SRC src_ip
  | lookup -r github_audit_events action name (category as ip_category name description)
  | iplookup -r github_cidr -e src_ip CIDR category as action_category
  | table repo src_ip ip_category CIDR action action_category description
```

