## 7. Alerts, Flows, Searches, and Scheduled Searches

Naming conventions for alerts, flows, searches, and scheduled searches help maintain consistency:
- **Naming Schema:** _QueryType - Company - Category - Severity - Name - [Visualization if any]_

#### Examples
- **Alert:** _Alert - GitHub - Category - Severity - Alertname_
    - _Example:_ Alert - GitHub - Account - Medium - Plan Changed
- **Flows:** _AlertFlow - GitHub - Category - Severity - Alertname_
    - _Example:_ AlertFlow - GitHub - Account - Medium - Plan Changed
- **Search:** _Search - GitHub - Category - Searchname [Visual Output Type]_
    - _Example:_ Search - GitHub - Code Scan - New Alerts [numbercard]
- **ScheduledSearch:** _ScheduledSearch - GitHub - Category - Searchname_
    - _Example:_ ScheduledSearch - GitHub - Code Scan - New Alerts

#### Alerts
- [Alerts] (https://docs.gravwell.io/alerts/alerts.html) are a Gravwell feature which allow the user to tie sources of intelligence (such as periodic scheduled searches) to actions (such as a flow that files a ticket). The Alerts within this kit are already setup with Dispatchers, Validation, and Consumers.
- Some basic terminology:
    - Events are the actual bits of actionable information, for instance \u201cA user signed in from outside the US\u201d.
    - Dispatchers generate events. A typical dispatcher would be a scheduled search that runs every hour looking for \u201cbad\u201d activity; every result returned by a scheduled search is considered an event.
    - Consumers process and respond to events. A typical consumer would be a flow that sends an email to an administrator, or opens a ticket in the ticketing system. Each consumer runs once per event.
    - Alerts tie dispatchers to consumers, ensuring that when a dispatcher generates an event, all associated consumers are executed to process it.
- Alert Flow
    - Dispatchers > Validation > Consumers
    - Scheduled Search > Common\_Field\_in\_log > Flows
    - ScheduledSearch > repo > AlertFlow
    - ScheduledSearch - GitHub - Category - Severity/Priority - ScheduledSearch\_Name > repo > AlertFlow - GitHub - Category - - Severity/Priority - AlertFlow\_Name

**Important:** If you change a Scheduled Search, you will effectively change the Alert, and the Flow.

- All Scheduled Searches, Alerts, & Flows are disabled by default, so you will need to do a couple of things in order to begin receiving any Alerts via Flows emailed to you.
1. Macros

  1.1 $GITHUB\_ALERT\_SENDER: This is the address to which GitHub Alert Flows will be sent from.
    - Update "replace\_me@with\_valid\_sender.address" to a valid email address you want to be the sender for GitHub Alerts

  1.2 $GITHUB\_ALERT\_RECIPIENT: This is the address to which GitHub Alert Flows will be sent to.
    - Update "replace\_me@with\_valid\_recipient.address" to a valid email address you want to be the recipient for GitHub Alerts

2. Scheduled Searches
    - You will need to enable each Scheduled Search that you want to to run.

3. Alerts
    - You will need to enable each Alert that you want to to run.

4. Flows
    - You will need to enable each Flow that you want to to run.
    - Cron Schedule
        - High: 3 \* \* \* \*
        - Medium: 15 \*/2 \* \* \*
        - Low: 27 \*/4 \* \* \*

